passages.text: 2Q GM came in higher at \(28.0\%\) (vs. \(23\%\) in 1Q25), better than our expectation due to product optimization. With opex also lower than expected, 2Q net income was better than our expectation at Rmb9mn, turning positive from 1Q25's Rmb18mn net loss. We are positive on Vanchip's migration to higher- end 5G PA modules (e.g. LPAMiD, LPAMiF) and product line expansions from cellular PA to WiFi PA, automotive PA and receiver products. However, we are cautious on the near- term trend given the modest growth of smartphone and markets, lack of major wireless technology upgrade cycle in near- term (6G still takes time) and continuous competition among RFFE players. Maintain Sell.

2Q25 GM beat on optimized product mix. Vanchip's 2Q25 revenues were down \(22\%\) YoY/ \(6\%\) QoQ, impacted by ongoing pricing pressure due to competitions. GM recovered to \(28.0\%\) , higher than GSe of \(22.8\%\) , which management attributed to their product optimization efforts. Opex also came in lower than expected at Rmb147mn, leading to better than expected operating loss of Rmb13m (vs. Rmb19m loss by GSe). Therefore, net income came in higher at Rmb9mn (vs. Rmb2mn by GSe), but was still down \(48\%\) YoY.
Exhibit 1:Vanchip:2025 earnings snapshot
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Better momentum in 2H25 driven by shipment of new products for smartphones. Management expect more high- end cellular PA modules to be shipped along with the new smartphone models launching this fall, supporting

better revenues growth in 3Q and 4Q. The company's Phase 7LE Plus LPAMiD modules will be equipped on the new flagship smartphone models this fall, and its Phase 8L LPAMiD has achieved mass shipment to leading smartphone brand customers. The company's low voltage LPAMiF modules will also be seen on new smartphones in 2H25, per management.

WiFi FEM supported by technology migrations. Management highlighted that revenues from WiFi 7 has surpassed that of WiFi 6 in 1H25, and WiFi 8 products are now in R&D. Vanchip is expanding to broader ranges of customers, from the traditional smartphones and routers to new applications such as drones, VR/AR, AI glasses and automotive.

Automotive grade products to drive future growth. Vanchip's automotive revenues have exceeded Rmb10m in 1H25. The company offers comprehensive solutions for automotive 5G RF front- end, and now developing 5G+WiFi combo modules and satellite modules, meeting the advancing communication demands on vehicles.

Earnings revision: We revise down 2025- 27E earnings by \(3\% /2\% /1\%\) , as a combined result of lower revenues, higher GM and lower opex. We revise down 2025- 27E revenues due to 1) the company's optimization towards higher GM products and the lower focus on low margin products, 2) the later than expected pricing recoveries, although pricing trend has been stabilized. We raised GM estimates on better product mix, while lower opex by \(6\% /4\% /3\%\) as we expect continuous expenses control measures.
Exhibit 2:Vanchip earnings revision
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Valuation: Our 12m TP for Vanchip to is unchanged at Rmb34.0. With the earnings revisions, our target PE is raised slightly to 69x 2026 P/E (vs. 68x previously), which is still derived from the sector correlation between 2026E P/E and avg. 2026- 27E earnings growth. The target PE is higher due to higher 2026- 27E earnings growth. With downside to the current TP, we have a Sell rating for Vanchip.
Exhibit 3: Derive target PE multiple (69x) based on sector regression between 2026E P/E and 2026-27E EPS YoY
Exhibit 4: Vanchip 12M forward P/E
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research, Bloomberg
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research, Bloomberg
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

While we are positive on Vanchip's product line expansion into the automotive market and its accumulated experience in consumer electronics' RF, we see downside risk for Vanchip given (1) softening smartphone demand growth globally, dragging down the company's RF shipments, and (2) the automotive business is still early stage. The company is currently trading at a higher multiple vs our target P/E of 69x, indicating a stretched valuation. We are Sell- rated on Vanchip.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
